If A^{p,q} is a bigraded object of \mathscr {A} such that






        A^{p,q}=0 except for a finite number of pairs (p,q), and





        A^{p,q}=0 for p+q\neq  n






    then we define two n-opposite filtrations of A=\sum _{p,q}A^{p,q} by setting

    741hodge-theory-ii-1.2.4.1hodge-theory-ii-1.2.4.1.xmlEquation1.2.4.1         F^p(A)         = \sum _{p'\geqslant  p} A^{p',q'}       \tag{1.2.4.1}       

    742hodge-theory-ii-1.2.4.2hodge-theory-ii-1.2.4.2.xmlEquation1.2.4.2         \overline {F}^q(A)         = \sum _{q'\geqslant  q} A^{p',q'}.       \tag{1.2.4.2}       

    We have

    743hodge-theory-ii-1.2.4.3hodge-theory-ii-1.2.4.3.xmlEquation1.2.4.3         \operatorname {Gr}_F^p\operatorname {Gr}_{\overline {F}}^q(A)         = A^{p,q}.       \tag{1.2.4.3}

