If f\colon  A\to  B is compatible with W, F, and \overline {F}, then we have

  753hodge-theory-ii-1.2.10.1hodge-theory-ii-1.2.10.1.xmlEquation1.2.10.1       f(A_i^{p,q})       \subset  B_i^{p,q}       \qquad \text {for }i=0,1.     \tag{1.2.10.1}     

  Claim (iii) then follows from the following lemma:

The A_i^{p,q} give a bigrading of A.
    We have

    755hodge-theory-ii-1.2.11.1hodge-theory-ii-1.2.11.1.xmlEquation1.2.11.1         W^n(A)         = \sum _{n+p+q\leqslant  0} A_i^{p,q}         \qquad \text {for }i=0,1       \tag{1.2.11.1}       

    756hodge-theory-ii-1.2.11.2hodge-theory-ii-1.2.11.2.xmlEquation1.2.11.2         F^p(A)         = \sum _{p'\geqslant  p} A_0^{p',q'}       \tag{1.2.11.2}       

    757hodge-theory-ii-1.2.11.3hodge-theory-ii-1.2.11.3.xmlEquation1.2.11.3         \overline {F}^q(A)         = \sum _{q'\geqslant  q} A_1^{p',q'}.       \tag{1.2.11.3}

By symmetry, it suffices to prove the claims concerning i=0. Set A_0=\bigoplus A_0^{p,q} and define filtrations W and F on A_0 by the equations of . The canonical map i from A_0 to A is compatible with the filtrations W and F. Furthermore, by , \operatorname {Gr}_W(i) is an isomorphism, and induces isomorphisms of graded objects
759hodge-theory-ii-1.2.11.4hodge-theory-ii-1.2.11.4.xmlEquation1.2.11.4 \sum _{p+q=n} A_0^{p,q} \xrightarrow {\sim } \operatorname {Gr}_W^{-n}(A) = \sum _{p+q=n} A^{p,q}. \tag{1.2.11.4}
The morphism i is thus an isomorphism, and the A_0^{p,q} give a bigrading of A.
